(AP) -- The government proposed to reduce federal protection of endangered gray wolves, saying they had successfully recovered from near extinction but acknowledging more could die as a result of the change. The Interior Department proposal would classify most of the wolves -- all those except the Mexican gray wolf in the Southwest -- as threatened rather than endangered. That means authorities would have greater leeway in developing management plans that take into account concerns from private landowners. The small population of Mexican gray wolves recently introduced to parts of New Mexico and Arizona -- only 22 wolves -- would
